\title{Token Dimension Compression for Scalable Context in Multimodal Large Language Models}
\begin{abstract}
Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs) face challenges in processing long visual-textual histories due to the quadratic cost of self-attention and the linear growth of the Key-Value (KV) cache. Existing solutions typically reduce token count, potentially trading fine-grained representation for more inputs.
This paper introduces token dimension compression, a paradigm that reduces the memory footprint of each token's representation while preserving all input tokens. 
We instantiate this with M$^2$LA, transforming attention blocks in pretrained LLMs into Multi-head Latent Attention (MLA) ones. MLA's low-rank latent space (storing keys and values) enables compact token representations dynamically. It is training-light, involving RoPE-aware positional aggregation and modality-aware adapters for diverse multimodal data.
M$^2$LA is a drop-in architectural change, maintaining near-lossless local context performance while achieving 2$\times$ KV-cache reductions and retaining over 99.5\% of the original accuracy, with even higher scores than original model in long-context regimes. This enables substantially longer multimodal contexts without sacrificing visual detail. Orthogonal to token-number reduction, M$^2$LA offers compounded memory savings, and empirical results on video benchmarks demonstrate significant gains in long-video understanding, establishing it as a broadly applicable solution for scaling MLLM context.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}
Multimodal large language models (MLLMs) are increasingly deployed as decision‑making and tool‑using agents, where success hinges on their ability to maintain, recall, and reason over long visual–textual histories \cite{comanici2025gemini,mu2023embodiedgpt,zhang2024chain}. From hour‑scale surveillance queries and multi‑page document understanding to long‑horizon GUI control and video editing, applications demand models that can ingest dense streams of visual tokens without forgetting early evidence or breaking temporal dependencies. Yet, despite recent progress in long‑context language modeling, extending multimodal context remains difficult: the cost of self‑attention is quadratic in sequence length, and the key–value (KV) cache grows linearly with tokens, quickly exhausting memory during autoregressive inference.
Most existing MLLMs address this by reducing visual token number before or during attention \cite{huang2025prunevid,bolya2023tome,zhang2025ivtp,chen2024image,li2024videochat}, besides of engineering solutions like sequence parallelism and data packing \cite{chen2024longvila,chen2025scaling,liu2024world}. Such token reductions include directly pooling or dropping them and indirectly cutting down input frames. These sometimes raise concerns about fine‑grained spatiotemporal cues missing and disrupted continuity. Consequently, accuracy on long‑range understanding or reasoning tasks often depends on carefully tuned and task‑specific token budgets.
This paper introduces and pursues a complementary and general paradigm: token dimension compression. Instead of reducing the count of tokens, this approach focuses on reducing the dimensionality of the representations that tokens occupy in the KV cache, thereby slimming their memory footprint. This paradigm compresses representations while preserving the full set of input tokens, offering a memory-efficient path to long multimodal context modeling without discarding potentially crucial information.
Concretely, we instantiate this token dimension compression paradigm with M$^2$LA, a new method that reparameterizes the Grouped-Query Attention (GQA) \cite{Ainslie23} blocks of a pretrained MLLM (Qwen2.5-VL \cite{bai2025qwen25vltechnicalreport}) into Multi-head Latent Attention (MLA) \cite{DeepSeek24}. In M$^2$LA, keys and values are stored in a shared, low-rank latent space and reconstructed on the fly via learned up-projections, allowing us to process substantially more visual evidence under the same memory budget. While our instantiation focuses on converting GQA to MLA, its principles about token dimension compression—namely RoPE-aware aggregation, low-rank factorization, and modality-aware adapters—constitute a relatively general schema. They can be applied to other attentions, including MLA ones for further optimization, offering a broadly applicable means for memory efficiency.
We instantiate these ideas in M$^2$LA, a training‑light procedure that converts a pretrained GQA block into its MLA form. The conversion proceeds via (i) RoPE‑aware aggregation of positional channels and (ii) low‑rank factorization of non‑positional channels, followed by lightweight, modality‑aware adapters that accommodate the distributional differences between text and vision. Crucially, this is a drop‑in architectural change: it preserves the model generation interface, requires only a small calibration pass or brief response‑style tuning, and yields near‑lossless behavior on short contexts while unlocking much longer multimodal contexts under the same memory budget.
Note token dimension compression is orthogonal to token number reduction. In practice, MLA‑based KV compression can be layered on top of sampling or merging pipelines to compound savings: pruning reduces the number of tokens; our method reduces the per‑token cache cost. This separation of concerns clarifies the design space for long multimodal context: token budgets manage redundancy at the input flow, while latent rank manages memory at the representation.
Empirically, we show that M$^2$LA enables 2–5× KV‑cache reductions over comparable GQA settings at matched quality on several video benchmarks, and it translates to tangible gains on long‑video understanding, multi‑page document QA, and long‑horizon tool use. Beyond raw capacity, the KV headroom can be reinvested to increase per‑head dimensionality, improving expressivity without exceeding the original memory envelope. Together, these results indicate that reparameterizing attention for KV‑cache efficiency is a simple, broadly applicable mechanism for scaling multimodal context—without sacrificing the visual details long‑range reasoning depends on.
Generally, this paper contributes as follows:
\begin{itemize}
    \item We introduce token-dimension compression as a general paradigm for long-context MLLMs, distinguishing it from token-number reduction. We instantiate this paradigm by reparameterizing GQA into MLA in Qwen2.5-VL, decoupling KV-cache size from the number of visual tokens. We propose M$^2$LA, a training-light conversion with RoPE-aware positional aggregation and low-rank non-positional factorization, augmented by modality-aware adapters for text and vision.
    \item We provide experiments showing near‑lossless short‑context accuracy, strong long‑context scaling, and improved memory–compute trade‑offs across video tasks: M$^2$LA cuts KV‑cache memory by about 50\% while preserving at least 99.5\% of baseline performance and even improving accuracy on long‑video benchmarks. 
\end{itemize}
\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:Related}
\begin{figure*}[t]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.9\linewidth]{pic/main.png}
    \caption{The framework of our {\method}. It converts general attention blocks into multi-head latent attention by re-structuring its computation while mostly inheriting weights. It consists of three steps that (1) reparameterize the attention blocks into MLA via RoPE-aware aggregation and low-rank factorization, (2) adapt to multimodal inputs using modality-aware adapters and visual latent budgeting, and (3) perform recovery training.}
    \label{fig:main}
\end{figure*}
\paragraph{Long Context Modeling in Multimodal Large Language Models.}
Handling long context has become the one of central challenges in Multimodal Large Language (MLLMs) \cite{comanici2025gemini,team2024gemini,wang2025dymu,zhang2025ivtp,li2024videochat,huang2025prunevid,wang2025internvideo2,li2025videochat,yan2025task,yan2025videochat,wang2022internvideo}, as high-resolution images, long videos, and large rich documents lead to severe token inflation. This primarily leads to token reduction strategies \cite{xue2024xgen,liu24,tong2025flashsloth,huang2025pgp,li2025mminference}. Foundational efforts such as BLIP-3~\cite{xue2024xgen} and LLaVA-NeXT~\cite{liu24} introduce efficient visual token compression via perceiver resamplers and dynamic resolution, enabling scalable multimodal fusion in form. 
FastV~\cite{chen2024image} exploits attention-based token pruning but is affected by task-agnostic biases (especially in spatial reasoning). IVTP~\cite{zhang2025ivtp} gives instruction-aware methods, leveraging pseudo-CLS tokens to align pruning with user queries. Concurrently, video-specific approaches like VideoChat-Flash \cite{li2024videochat} and PruneVid~\cite{huang2025prunevid} harness spatiotemporal redundancy via hierarchical merging. 
Besides of token reduction, some studies explore developing context capacity from long corpus training, inference extrapolation, and short-form representation for long inputs.
LongVA~\cite{Zhang24} demonstrates that long-context capacity from text-only pretraining can transfer to vision without video-specific training. Building on these, recent models co-design vision encoders, positional embeddings, and attention mechanisms for extreme-length inputs: Qwen2.5-VL~\cite{bai2025qwen25vltechnicalreport} and Qwen3-VL~\cite{yang2025qwen3technicalreport} support native 256K-token contexts and extend to 1M tokens via YaRN-based extrapolation and interleaved mRoPE, enabling precise spatiotemporal reasoning in hour-long videos. Similarly, InternVL3~\cite{zhu2025internvl3exploringadvancedtraining} and InternVL3.5~\cite{wang2025internvl35advancingopensourcemultimodal} integrate dynamic high-resolution visual encoding with long-context LLM backbones, scaling to 128K tokens for document- and video understanding. 
\paragraph{Efficient Attention.}
The evolution of attention mechanisms in LLMs has been driven by the need for greater token throughput and expanded context handling.
Starting from standard multi-head attention (MHA) \cite{Vaswani17}, variants like Multi-query attention (MQA) \cite{Shazeer19} and Grouped-query attention (GQA) \cite{Ainslie23} emerge to reduce KV cache memory by sharing or grouping key-value heads, balancing efficiency with expressivity. Further advancements, such as Multi-Head Latent Attention (MLA) \cite{DeepSeek24} and Multi-Matrix Factorization Attention (MFA) \cite{Step325}, dramatically compress the KV state by projecting keys and values into low-rank latent spaces or using structured decompositions, significantly shrinking cache size with negligible performance loss. For long-context modeling, specialized approaches like DeepSeek's Native Sparse Attention (NSA) \cite{DeepSeekNSA25} and GLM-4.5's combination of GQA with partial rotary positional embedding \cite{GLM4525} enhance context fidelity without inflating cache. These efficient attention architectures are crucial for improving the context capacity of multimodal large language models (MLLMs). While recent works have explored integrating GQA with MLA in text models \cite{ji2025mha2mla, meng2025transmla}, this promising implementation has not yet been explored within the visual domain.

\section{Method}
\label{sec:method}
We aim to enable long context visual-language modeling by reducing KV-cache memory while preserving the expressivity and positional fidelity of attention. We first revisit Group-Query Attention (GQA) and Multi-Head Latent Attention (MLA), isolating where memory is spent and how positional encoding interact with KV sharing. Regarding this, we introduce M$^2$LA, a multimodal multi-head latent attention that reparametrizes a GQA block into an MLA form. This is achieved via a lightweight calibration, followed by modality-specific adapters to handle the distinct statistical properties of text and visual tokens. An overview of our approach is illustrated in Figure~\ref{fig:main}. 
\subsection{Preliminaries}
\label{subsec:gqa-mla}
We begin with revisiting two prominent efficient attention mechanisms, Grouped-Query Attention (GQA) and Multi-Head Latent Attention (MLA), to analyze their respective approaches in reducing KV cache bottleneck.
\paragraph{Background and Notation.}
As shown in \cref{fig:attention_arc}, standard Multi-Head Attention (MHA) computes queries ($\bm{Q}$), keys ($\bm{K}$), and values ($\bm{V}$) from an input sequence $\bm{X}\in\mathbb{R}^{T\times d}$. These are split into $H$ heads, and attention is computed for each head. During autoregressive inference, $\bm{K}$ and $\bm{V}$ tensors, known as the KV cache, are stored and grow linearly with the sequence length $T$. For long sequences with visual tokens, this cache becomes the primary memory bottleneck.
\paragraph{GQA.}
GQA mitigates this issue by grouping query heads and having all heads within a group share a single key and value projection. If MHA has $H$ heads, GQA partitions them into $G$ groups (where $G < H$). For a head $h$ in group $g(h)$, the attention is:
\begin{equation}
  \mathrm{Attn}^{(h)}(X)=\mathrm{softmax}\!\left(\frac{Q^{(h)}{K^{(g(h))}}^\top}{\sqrt{d_h}}\right)V^{(g(h))},
  \label{eq:gqa}
\end{equation}
where KV cache is reduced from $O(HTd_h)$ to $O(GTd_h)$, offering a trade-off between memory and performance. 
\paragraph{MLA.} MLA offers a different strategy by compressing the key and value tensors into a shared low-rank latent representation. Instead of reducing the number of KV heads, MLA jointly compresses $\bm{K}$ and $\bm{V}$ into a latent vector $\bm{z}_t \in \mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{latent}}}$. It decouples positional information from content by splitting each head's channels into a non-positional part (nope) and a Rotary Position Embedding part (rope).
Specifically, for each token $\bm{x}_t$, MLA computes:
\begin{align}
    \bm{q}_t &= \bm{x}_t \bm{W}_q \in \mathbb{R}^{n_h (d_{\text{nope}} + d_{\text{rope}})}, \\
    \bm{z}_t &= \bm{x}_t \bm{W}_{\text{kv}} \in \mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{rope}} + d_{\text{latent}}}, \\
    \bm{k}_t^{\text{nope}} &= \bm{z}_t^{\text{latent}} \bm{U}_K \in \mathbb{R}^{n_g d_{\text{nope}}}, \\
    \bm{v}_t &= \bm{z}_t^{\text{latent}} \bm{U}_V \in \mathbb{R}^{n_g d_v}
\end{align}
The RoPE component $\tilde{\bm{k}}_t^{\text{rope}}$ is derived from $\bm{z}_t^{\text{rope}}$ and shared across all heads (MQA-style), while the non-positional keys $\bm{k}_t^{\text{nope}}$ are generated from the latent space via an up-projection matrix $\bm{U}K$. The full keys are a concatenation of these components. The key insight is that MLA caches only the compact latent vector $\bm{z}_t$ and the shared RoPE component, leading to a KV cache size of $O(T(d_{\text{latent}} + d_{\text{rope}}))$. This is much smaller than GQA's $O(GTd_h)$, as MLA achieves better performance with a smaller memory footprint by preserving head diversity through up-projection. 
\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.95\linewidth]{pic/attention_arc.png}
  \caption{Attention architectures. }
  \label{fig:attention_arc}
\end{figure}

\subsection{M$^2$LA: Reparameterizing Attention for Efficient Multimodal Context}
\label{subsec:m2la}
We propose a method to convert a pre-trained GQA block into an equivalent MLA block. This allows us to inherit the benefits of a pre-trained model while leveraging the superior memory efficiency of MLA. The process involves two main steps: compressing the positional channels and factorizing the non-positional channels. This idea is inspired by recent work in LLMs \cite{meng2025transmla}, which we adapt and extend for the unique challenges of multimodal video understanding.
\subsubsection{Reparameterization}
\paragraph{RoPE-Aware Aggregation via PCA.}
Rotary Position Embeddings (RoPE) apply position-dependent rotations to query and key vectors. A key property is that the inner product between queries and keys is preserved under any position-independent unitary transform. We leverage this to compress the RoPE components from $H$ heads into a single shared key.
Specifically, considering the unitary transform $U$ needs to capture essentials of the given rope keys with a linear compression, a feasible solution is to exploit the eigenvectors of the cross-head covariance matrix to form the unitary basis, as follows:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Activation Collection and Complexification:} We first pass a small, representative calibration dataset through the model to collect the key activations \(\mathbf{k}^{(h)} \in \mathbb{R}^{d_h}\) for each head \(h=1, \dots, H\) at a specific layer. We then transform these real vectors into their complex counterparts \(\mathbf{z}^{(h)} \in \mathbb{C}^{d_c}\).
    \item \textbf{Cross-Head Complex PCA:} For each complex dimension \(m = 1, \dots, d_c\), we construct a vector \(\mathbf{v}_m \in \mathbb{C}^H\) by stacking the \(m\)-th component from all heads, \(\mathbf{v}_m = [z^{(1)}_m, \dots, z^{(H)}_m]^T\). We then compute the cross-head covariance matrix \(\mathbf{C}_m = \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{v}_m \mathbf{v}_m^H]\) and find its principal eigenvector, \(\mathbf{u}_m \in \mathbb{C}^H\). This eigenvector \(\mathbf{u}_m\) represents the direction of maximum variance for the \(m\)-th complex feature across all heads.
    \item \textbf{Shared Key Construction:} The set of principal eigenvectors \(\{\mathbf{u}_m\}_{m=1}^{d_c}\) defines our projection. To obtain the shared key, we project the multi-head vectors onto this principal basis:
    \begin{equation}
        s_m = \mathbf{u}_m^H \mathbf{v}_m, \quad \text{for } m = 1, \dots, d_c.
    \end{equation}
    This yields a shared complex vector \(\mathbf{s} = [s_1, \dots, s_{d_c}]^T \in \mathbb{C}^{d_c}\). Finally, we de-complexify \(\mathbf{s}\) back into a real-valued vector \(\mathbf{k}_{\text{shared}} \in \mathbb{R}^{d_h}\) by interleaving its real and imaginary parts. This vector serves as the key for the new MQA head.
\end{enumerate}
\paragraph{Low‑Rank Factorization for Non‑Positional Channels.}
For the non-positional channels, which are already shared within GQA groups, we introduce a low-rank bottleneck. Let the concatenated group-wise non-positional keys be $K_\text{nope} \in \mathbb{R}^{T \times (Gd_\text{nope})}$. We aim to find a latent representation $Z = X W_{kv} \in \mathbb{R}^{T \times C}$ (with $C \ll Gd_\text{nope}$) and up-projection matrices $U_K, U_V$ such that:
\begin{equation}
K_\text{nope} \approx Z U_K, \quad V_\text{nope} \approx Z U_V
\end{equation}
The matrices $W_{kv}$, $U_K$, and $U_V$ are estimated via least squares on the cached activations from the calibration set. During inference, we only cache $Z$, reconstructing the full keys and values on the fly.
\subsubsection{Adapting to Multimodal Inputs}
The reparameterization gives an efficient attention. We now introduce M$^2$LA by adapting this block for MLLMs that process both text and a number of visual tokens.
\paragraph{Modality-Aware Adapters.} While tokens from all modalities share a temporal sequence, their distributions differ. We use lightweight modality-specific linear adapters $A_\text{txt}$, $A_\text{vis}$ on top of $Z$, applied to the latent representation:
\begin{equation}
    K_\text{nope}^{\text{mod}} \approx (Z A_{\text{mod}}) U_K, V_\text{nope}^{\text{mod}} \approx (Z A_{\text{mod}}) U_V,
\end{equation}
where $\text{mod} \in \{ \text{txt}, \text{vis}\}$. These adapters are initialized as identity matrices and can be optionally fine-tuned to specialize the latent space for each modality without altering the shared projection heads.
\paragraph{Visual Latent Budgeting.} 
Leveraging modality-aware adapters enables us to allocate different latent dimensions across modalities according to their information content and task importance. Recent work \cite{lin2025boosting,li2024videochat} observes that, as representations propagate from lower to higher layers in causal LLMs, the unidirectional nature of self-attention induces information migration: information in earlier visual tokens gradually shifts into later text tokens, leading visual tokens to receive diminishing attention and to become less important at higher layers. This suggests that the memory devoted to visual tokens should shrink with depth, calling for a more dynamic mechanism. Migrating to an MLA architecture affords precisely this flexibility: rather than discarding tokens or forcibly merging them, we dynamically adjust the ranks used when compressing and storing keys and values in MLA—i.e., the latent dimension.
To guide visual budgeting and evaluate the impact of visual compression, we use Multimodal Perplexity (MMPPL). Perplexity is a standard metric for evaluating a language model's confidence, where lower values indicate the model is less ``surprised" by the target, reflecting a better grasp of the underlying data distribution. We adapt this measurement in our work.
Let a video $V = \{f_t\}_{t=1}^{T}$ be processed by a frozen vision-language model $M_\theta$ with a task prompt $c$. For a target text sequence $Y = (y_1,\dots,y_N)$, MMPPL is as:
\begin{multline}
\mathrm{MMPPL}(V, c, \mathbf{r}, \mathbf{M}; \theta) = \exp\!\big(\mathcal{L}_{\text{NLL}}(Y \mid V, c, \mathbf{r}, \mathbf{M}; \theta)\big). \\  \text{w.r.t} \quad
\mathcal{L}_{\text{NLL}}(Y \mid V, c, \mathbf{r}, \mathbf{M}; \theta) = \\
- \frac{1}{\sum_{t=1}^{N} r_t} \sum_{t=1}^{N} r_t \, \log p_\theta\!\left(y_t \,\middle|\, y_{<t},\, V \odot \mathbf{M},\, c\right)
\end{multline}
where $\mathbf{M}$ is a visual mask representing the transformation (e.g., frame sampling), and $\mathbf{r}$ is a language mask to score only relevant tokens (e.g., the answer in a Q\&A task). A lower MMPPL signifies that the transformed video $V$ retains more utility for the model to predict the target $Y$. 
\subsubsection{Analysis}
\paragraph{Why Share RoPE but Adapt Content?}
Our design to share the RoPE across all modalities while using adapters for non-positional content is deliberate. RoPE encodes the absolute position of a token within the global sequence, sound for both text and images. This shared positional awareness is crucial for understanding temporal order. In contrast, the adapters operate on the content of the tokens, allowing the model to handle the notable distributional shift between the semantic spaces of language and vision without requiring separate attention blocks.
\paragraph{Efficiency.}
The reparameterized M$^2$LA block significantly reduces the KV cache. For a typical configuration ($H=32, G=4, d_k=128$), our method can yield a near 2x reduction in KV cache size over GQA and over 10x compared to MHA. This saving can be reinvested to increase performance, for instance, by using larger head dimensions ($d_h$) to enhance the model's expressive power without exceeding the memory budget of the original model. The only computational overhead during inference is a negligible low-rank up-projection per step.
\paragraph{Adaptation to Other Attentions.} 
Though we mainly use GQA in attention reparametrization for illustration and experimentation, the proposed {\method} is also applicable to other attention variants (e.g. MHA, MQA, etc) and even naive MLA itself \cite{DeepSeek24}. DeepSeek's MLA, as a general efficient attention mechanism, might process both text and visual tokens through the same latent space and up-projection matrices. While efficient, this shared processing might not optimally account for the distinct statistical properties and information distribution of different modalities. {\method}'s modality-aware adapters address this by allowing the shared latent space to be specialized for each modality after the initial compression. Moreover, {\method} proposes dynamically adjusting the latent dimension used for visual tokens based on depth or importance. An existing MLA could be modified to implement this by having layer-dependent latent dimensions for visual tokens. Regarding this, {\method} can lead to enhanced multimodal understanding with more aggressive compression even on original MLA.
\subsection{Tuning MLLMs with {\method}}
As emphasized, {\method} is pluigible to existing mainstream MLLMs and only need a swift tuning to recover its original capabilities. We detail its training data and recipe as follows. Before that, we also introduce a lite multimodal input decoration approach for improving its temporal sensitivity.

