\paragraph{Frame Landmarks.} \label{sec:framelandmark}
To address the challenges of temporal grounding and long-range attention decay in multimodal contexts, we introduce \emph{frame landmarks}, serving as a salient human-interpretable summaries for clips. They are short textual anchors inserted \emph{at the end} of fixed-size frame groups. Specifically, given a video, its frames are encoded into a sequence of vision tokens, and these tokens are partitioned into groups of $n$ frames. Then we append a textual landmark $\ell_k$, explicitly encoding its covered frame range (e.g., \texttt{Frame0~n-1}). The complete multimodal input sequence is constructed by combining an optional textual prefix ($X_{\text{txt}}^{\text{pre}}$), followed by pairs of vision tokens ($V_{\mathcal{G}k}$) and their corresponding landmarks ($\ell_k$) for each group, and finally, an optional textual suffix ($X_{\text{txt}}^{\text{post}}$). This results in the input structure:
\begin{equation}
X=\big[X_{\text{txt}}^{\text{pre}};,\big(V_{\mathcal{G}1},,\ell_1\big),,\dots,,\big(V_{\mathcal{G}K},\ell_K\big);;X_{\text{txt}}^{\text{post}}\big].
\end{equation}
This placement of landmarks, combined with a causal attention mask, allows each landmark to aggregate its group's visual evidence before becoming available to subsequent text tokens. 
Intuitively, textual queries can then retrieve visuals via a shorter, two-hop path (text $\!\to\!$ landmark $\!\to\!$ group) alongside the standard direct attention to all vision tokens. Rather than restricting access, landmarks emphasize attention toward temporally localized summaries. This organizes retrieval around $\mathcal{O}(T/n)$ anchors that complement full token-level attention with minimal overhead (only $K$ additional tokens), while preserving fine-grained details through each landmark's local aggregation. Empirically, we find that these landmarks improve long-context stability and frame-level localization without altering the underlying attention mechanism or training objective, as validated in Section \ref{sec:ab_fp}.
\paragraph{Training Data.}
To ensure a fair comparison, we follow VideoChat-Flash~\cite{li2024videochat} and employ the same training corpus of stage 3 for training. Specifically, our dataset comprises 3.5 million instruction tuning samples, including 1.1 million images, 1.7 million short videos (each under 60 seconds), 
and 0.7 million long videos (ranging from 60 to 3600 seconds). By combining short and long video data, we aim to enhance the model’s capacity for long-form video comprehension while preserving its ability to capture fine-grained visual details.
\paragraph{Learning.} 
Our model is trained on the aforementioned dataset by freezing the visual encoder and tuning only the connector and LLM components. This approach enables us to achieve strong performance quickly and with minimal computational overhead. Unlike prior methods that often rely on comprehensive multi-stage training pipelines \cite{li2024videochat,shu2025video,liu2025video,qin2025video}, we employ a single training phase. We achieve this by effectively packing and training short and long videos together, demonstrating results comparable to multi-stage alternatives.

\section{Experiments}
\label{sec:experiments}
\paragraph{Implementation Details.}
Building upon QwenVL2.5, we replace its vision encoder with UMT-L \cite{li2023unmasked} (a ViT encoder specialized for spatiotemporal tasks) for aligning with VideoChat-Flash \cite{li2024videochat}. The LLM uses Qwen2.5-7B-1M for context length. When processing long videos, we divide them into clips, each having 4 frames. 
As we also leverage token reduction strategy used in VideoChat-Flash, we name our MLLM as VideoChat-{\method}. We fine-tune VideoChat-{\method} end-to-end for video instruction tuning on 16 NVIDIA A100 GPUs using DeepSpeed ZeRO-1. The language model and MLP adapters are jointly optimized for seamless multimodal integration.
For key hyperparameters, the learning rate is set to $1 \times 10^{-5}$ with cosine decay and 0.05 warmup ratio. We use 16 gradient accumulation steps and per-device batch size is 1, with the maximum sequence length of 32,768 tokens. Mixed-precision training (bf16 with TF32) ensures computational efficiency and stability.
Gradient checkpointing is enabled to handle long sequences with minimal VRAM usage. For images, we use anyres\_nopad tiling with pad-free spatial fusion to remove padding artifacts and support variable-resolution inputs.
\paragraph{Benchmarks.}
We evaluate our approach along with popular MLLMs on multimodal video understanding benchmarks on a multiple-choice question-answering format, including short video benchmark like MVBench \cite{li2024mvbench} ,temporal grounding benchmark like Charades-STA\cite{gao2017tall}, and three relatively long video benchmarks like LongVideoBench \cite{wu2024longvideobench}, MLVU \cite{zhou2024mlvu}, LVBench \cite{wang2025lvbench}, and VideoMME \cite{fu2025video}, covering footage ranging from seconds-level to hour-level durations.
